In MAUI, `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on the `Application` class and work as before. However, MAUI also introduces more granular **Window lifecycle events**, which is the recommended approach:

**Option 1 — Override `CreateWindow` in `App.cs`:**
```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };
    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };
    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };
    window.Destroying += (s, e) => { /* cleanup */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Option 2 — Platform-specific hooks in `MauiProgram.cs`:**
```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android =>
    {
        android.OnStart((activity) => { /* ... */ });
        android.OnStop((activity) => { /* ... */ });
    });
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios =>
    {
        ios.WillFinishLaunching((app, dict) => { /* ... */ return true; });
        ios.OnActivated((app) => { /* ... */ });
    });
#endif
});
```

**Quick mapping:**

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event |
|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `Window.Created` |
| `OnSleep()` | `Window.Stopped` |
| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed` |

The Window approach is preferred because MAUI supports multi-window apps (especially on desktop), so per-window lifecycle tracking is more precise.
